ll,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAcute kidney injury is classified into three main categories based on the anatomical location and mechanism:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPre-renal: caused by reduced kidney perfusion (including \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal artery stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edehydration\u003C/strong\u003E)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIntrinsic renal: caused by direct damage to kidney tissue (including \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute glomerulonephritis\u003C/strong\u003E)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPost-renal: caused by urinary tract obstruction (including \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteric calculus\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostatic enlargement\u003C/strong\u003E)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcute glomerulonephritis represents inflammation and damage to the glomeruli within the kidney itself, making it an intrinsic renal cause. Other intrinsic causes include acute tubular necrosis, interstitial nephritis, and vasculitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute kidney injury is classified into pre-renal (decreased perfusion), intrinsic renal (kidney damage), and post-renal (obstructive) causes","Pre-renal causes include conditions that reduce kidney perfusion like shock or volume depletion","Post-renal causes include any obstruction to urinary outflow from the kidneys to the external environment","Intrinsic renal causes involve direct damage to kidney structures including glomeruli, tubules, interstitium or vessels"],"references":["Jennette, J. C., \u0026 D\u0027Agati, V. D. (2023). Heptinstall\u0027s Pathology of the Kidney. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kellum JA, Romagnani P, Ashuntantang G, Ronco C, Zarbock A, Anders HJ. Acute kidney injury. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2021 Jul 15;7(1):52. doi: 10.1038/s41572-021-00284-z. PMID: 34267223.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Koeppen, B. M., \u0026 Stanton, B. A. (2018). Renal Physiology E-Book: Renal Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52641"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15030"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52641"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-03T22:40:01+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-03T22:40:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7718"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67185"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4933"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urinary","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"da